=========================================================
VIRTUAL FUNCTION INTERNAL WORKING ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
=========================================================

Definition
----------

A virtual function enables Runtime Polymorphism.

The function to execute is determined at Runtime,
not Compile Time.

=========================================================
Example
=========================================================

#include<iostream>
using namespace std;

class Base
{
public:

    virtual void display()
    {
        cout<<"Base"<<endl;
    }
};

class Derived : public Base
{
public:

    void display() override
    {
        cout<<"Derived"<<endl;
    }
};

int main()
{
    Base* ptr = new Derived;

    ptr->display();
}

Output

Derived

=========================================================
Question
=========================================================

How does compiler know to call Derived::display() ?

Answer

Using

1. vtable
2. vptr

=========================================================
Step 1 : Compiler Creates Virtual Table (vtable)
=========================================================

Whenever a class contains at least ONE virtual function,

Compiler automatically creates a table called

Virtual Table (vtable)

It stores addresses of virtual functions.

---------------------------------------------------------
Base Class
---------------------------------------------------------

class Base
{
public:

    virtual void display();
};

Compiler conceptually creates

Base vtable

--------------------------
display()  ---> Base::display
--------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------
Derived Class
---------------------------------------------------------

class Derived : public Base
{
public:

    void display();
};

Compiler creates another table

Derived vtable

-----------------------------
display() ---> Derived::display
-----------------------------

Every polymorphic class gets its own vtable.

=========================================================
Step 2 : Compiler Adds vptr
=========================================================

Compiler secretly adds one hidden pointer
inside every object.

Called

Virtual Pointer

(vptr)

Programmer never writes it.

Conceptually

class Base
{
    vptr;

    virtual void display();
};

Object Layout

----------------------

Base Object

+-----------------+
| vptr            |
+-----------------+

=========================================================
Step 3 : Constructor Initializes vptr
=========================================================

When object is created,

Constructor initializes

vptr

to point to the class's vtable.

---------------------------------------------------------

Base b;

Constructor sets

b.vptr

↓

Base vtable

---------------------------------------------------------

Derived d;

Constructor sets

d.vptr

↓

Derived vtable

