=========================================================
Multiple Virtual Functions
=========================================================

class Base
{
public:

    virtual void f1();

    virtual void f2();

    virtual void f3();
};

Compiler creates

Base vtable

----------------------------

f1 -> Base::f1

f2 -> Base::f2

f3 -> Base::f3

----------------------------

Only ONE vptr exists per object.

Not one vptr per virtual function.

=========================================================
Inheritance Example
=========================================================

class Base
{
public:

    virtual void f1();

    virtual void f2();
};

class Derived : public Base
{
public:

    void f2() override;

    virtual void f3();
};

Derived vtable

------------------------------------

f1 -> Base::f1

f2 -> Derived::f2

f3 -> Derived::f3

------------------------------------

Functions not overridden continue to
point to the base implementation.

=========================================================
Performance Cost
=========================================================

Advantages

✓ Runtime Polymorphism

✓ Flexible Design

✓ Extensible Code

---------------------------------------------------------

Overheads

✓ One hidden pointer (vptr)

✓ One vtable per class

✓ One extra pointer dereference during call

Usually negligible.

=========================================================
Most Asked Interview Questions
=========================================================

Q. What is vtable?

A compiler-generated table that stores addresses
of virtual functions.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What is vptr?

A hidden pointer inside every object of a polymorphic
class that points to the class's vtable.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Who creates the vtable?

Compiler.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Who initializes vptr?

Constructor.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Where is vptr stored?********IIIMP

Inside every object.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Where is vtable stored?

Compiler-dependent, typically in read-only memory
or a static data section.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. How many vptrs are there?

One per object.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. How many vtables are there?

One per polymorphic class.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Does every object have a vtable?

No.

Objects have a vptr.

Classes have a vtable.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Does a class without virtual functions have a vptr?

No.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Does virtual increase object size?

Yes.

Typically by the size of one pointer.

=========================================================
Interview Answer (1 Minute)
=========================================================

"A virtual function enables runtime polymorphism. Internally, the
compiler creates a virtual table (vtable) for every class that has
virtual functions. The vtable stores the addresses of the virtual
functions. Every object of such a class contains a hidden pointer
called the vptr, which is initialized by the constructor to point
to the appropriate vtable. When a virtual function is called through
a base class pointer or reference, the compiler generates code that
looks up the function address through the object's vptr and invokes
the correct function at runtime. This is why a Base* pointing to a
Derived object correctly calls Derived's overridden implementation."
